  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "كَانَ and Its Sisters",
      "titleArabic": "كَانَ وَأَخَوَاتُهَا",
      "content": [
        "كَانَ (was/were) and its 'sisters' are incomplete verbs that enter upon nominal sentences. Unlike إِنَّ, they keep the subject nominative but change the predicate to accusative.",
        "The main sisters include: كَانَ (was), أَصْبَحَ (became, in morning), أَمْسَى (became, in evening), صَارَ (became), and لَيْسَ (is not)."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "كَانَ (was/were) - for past states: كَانَ الطَّالِبُ مُجْتَهِدًا",
        "صَارَ/أَصْبَحَ (became) - for change of state",
        "لَيْسَ (is not) - for present negation",
        "Subject stays nominative, predicate becomes accusative"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "كَانَ الطَّالِبُ مُجْتَهِدًا", "english": "The student was diligent" },
        { "arabic": "كَانَ الْبَيْتُ كَبِيرًا", "english": "The house was big" },
        { "arabic": "أَصْبَحَ الْوَلَدُ طَالِبًا", "english": "The boy became a student" },
        { "arabic": "لَيْسَ الْبَيْتُ كَبِيرًا", "english": "The house is not big" }
      ]
    }
  ],
